Preclinical evidence. This herbal medicine has been experimentally proven for cough. An ethanol extract of 
 P. lanceolata reduces the number of coughs provoked by citric acid, in guinea-pig, in a similar way to codeine (
 Boskabady et al., 2006a). Other experiments showed that an ethanol extract of this species inhibited the barium-induced contraction of guinea-pig isolated trachea (
 Fleer and Verspohl, 2007). The pharmacological effects described in literature support both the oral and oromucosal traditional use of herbal preparations of 
 P. lanceolata as a demulcent for the symptomatic treatment of oral and pharyngeal mucosa irritation, associated to dry cough (
 Ortiz de Urbina et al., 1994; 
 Herold et al., 2003; 
 Vigo et al., 2005; 
 Hausmann et al., 2007).
